A practical order is:

Create the problem + basic metadata

name, time limit, memory limit, tags if you care later.

Write the statement first

legend, input, output, notes, examples framing.

This forces you to pin down ambiguity early.

Write the validator

On Codeforces/Polygon, validators are strongly recommended and effectively required for proper CF use, especially because hack tests are validated too.

Write the main correct solution

the official/reference solution Polygon can use to generate expected outputs.

Write the generator(s)

random, max, structured, adversarial, special cases.

Create the test script / test groups

usually with sample tests first, then hand tests, then generated stress/adversarial tests.

Polygon test scripts typically point generated inputs to official outputs via > $.

Generate and inspect tests

make sure coverage is real, not just volume.

Polygon now warns about incomplete tests when validator-observed bounds are not hit; that warning is meant to be taken seriously.

Add checker if needed

only if the output is non-unique / special judge.

Otherwise standard comparison is enough.

Add bad / alternate solutions

greedy WA, borderline TLE, overflow bugs, etc.

run them against the test set to confirm the tests actually separate them.

Use invocations / local testing repeatedly

test validator, checker, generator, and solutions before packaging. Polygon has dedicated support for validator/checker tests too.

Build package

fix warnings, verify samples, statements, file names, limits.

Only then worry about contest integration / sharing

permissions, coauthors, package export, import into contest.
